spirit:component.spirit:description: The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) is a computationally efficient algorithm for computing the Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT). The FFT Core can compute 8 to 65536-point forward or inverse complex transforms on up to 12 parallel channels. The input data is a vector of complex values represented as two's-complement numbers 8 to 34 bits wide or single precision floating point numbers 32 bits wide. The phase factors can be 8 to 34 bits wide. All memory is on-chip using either Block RAM or Distributed RAM. Three arithmetic types are available: full-precision unscaled, scaled fixed-point, and block-floating point. Several parameters are run-time configurable: the point size, the choice of forward or inverse transform, and the scaling schedule. Four architectures are available to provide a tradeoff between size and transform time.
